ely tight band between roughly 111.20 and 112.80. That base-building phase culminated in a decisive bullish expansion on 14 July, when the daily candle closed above 113.17 \u2014 a level that had previously capped multiple recovery attempts. The following two sessions have extended that move, with yesterday printing a high of 113.88 before settling back toward current levels. The broader structure has shifted from one of post-drop consolidation to a tentative recovery phase, though the desk's bias remains neutral given that price has not yet cleared the next meaningful overhead zone.\n\nThat overhead zone sits at the 113.97 prior reaction area, which has registered three touches on the data and represents the first credible test for bulls to navigate. Beyond that, a more established resistance cluster lies near 114.33, a level where sellers have previously reasserted themselves on multiple occasions. To the downside, the 113.20 prior reaction zone \u2014 which acted as resistance through much of the mid-June period \u2014 has now flipped to a candidate support reference. A deeper pullback would bring the 112.85 structure into focus, a zone that offered meaningful support during the July consolidation.\n\nOn the hourly chart, the picture is one of controlled digestion following the overnight push to 113.88. Price has drifted back into the 113.55\u2013113.65 range across the past several hours, with each dip finding modest support rather than accelerating lower. The hourly sequence of higher lows from the 113.29 trough during the London morning of 16 July remains broadly intact, suggesting the short-term momentum has not been meaningfully disrupted. The 113.28\u2013113.30 area on the hourly represents the level that would call the intraday structure into question if revisited with conviction.\n\nToday's economic calendar carries no scheduled high-impact events for either the Australian dollar or the Japanese yen, which points to a session likely driven by broader risk sentiment and cross-market flows rather than data-driven volatility. Thin catalysts can sometimes allow technical levels to hold with greater clarity, but they can equally leave the pair susceptible to sharp moves if equity markets or US dollar dynamics shift unexpectedly.\n\nThe bullish read from the daily recovery would be challenged on a daily close back beneath 113.20, which would suggest the breakout above prior resistance has failed to hold. Conversely, a clean daily close above 113.97 would open the narrative toward the 114.33 resistance cluster and potentially shift the desk's neutral bias toward a more constructive tilt.\n\nThis is editorial analysis, not financial advice. Trading involves substantial risk of loss.", "sample": false}